<section xml:id="sect-function-intervals">
  <title>Functions Defined on Intervals</title>

  <p>
    We know turn to defining a function on an interval.
    It is natural to define
    <me>
    f(\boldsymbol{x}) = \{ y \; | \; y=f(x), x \in \boldsymbol{x}\}
  </me>
  where <m>\boldsymbol{x}</m> is an interval as defined in this chapter.
    In many cases, this is well-defined.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>A=[-1,1]</m>, <m>B=[0,\pi]</m> and <m>C=[1,9]</m>.
        Then
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>  e^A \amp = [e^{-1},e] </mrow>
          <mrow> \sin(B) \amp =  [0,1]</mrow>
          <mrow>\sqrt{C} \amp = [1,3]</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
</section>